P ‚Ä≤RQ‚Ä≤.
We write P <‚àº Q if PRQ for some expansion R. Relation <‚àº is a preorder
and a congruence.
2.1 Encoding the lazy Œª-calculus into the asynchronous polyadic
pi-calculus.
The transfer of results from the Œª-calculus to the asynchronous polyadic pi-
calculus is achieved by using the encoding of the lazy Œª-calculus described below.
Definition 1. [2, 3, 8] The set Œõ of Œª-terms is defined by the following grammar,
where x ranges over the set of Œª-calculus variables:
M ::= x | Œªx.M | MN
Free variables, closed terms, substitution, alpha-conversion etc. are defined as
usual. The reduction relation is ‚àí‚Üí, and the reflexive and transitive closure of
‚àí‚Üí is =‚áí. We write M ‚Üì if M is convergent, and M ‚Üë otherwise. In the lazy
Œª-calculus [1], the redex is always at the left extreme of a term.
The proofs in Section 5 need the following tools:
Theorem 1. [3] The predicate ‚ÄòM ‚Üì‚Äô is undecidable.
Definition 2. [6, 8] The encoding of the lazy Œª-calculus into the asynchronous
