2.3 Modified Realizability
Clearly proper existence proofs have computational content. A well-known and
natural way to define this concept is the notion of realizability, which can be seen
as an incarnation of the Brouwer-Heyting-Kolmogorov interpretation of proofs.
Type of a Formula We define œÑ(œï) as the type of the term (or ‚Äúprogram‚Äù) to
be extracted from a proof of œï. More precisely, we assign to every formula œï an
object œÑ(œï) (a type or the ‚Äúnulltype‚Äù symbol Œµ). In case œÑ(œï) = Œµ proofs of œï
have no computational content; such formulas œï are called Harrop formulas. The
definition can be conveniently written if we extend the use of œÅ‚Üí œÉ and œÅ√ó œÉ,
to the nulltype symbol: (œÅ ‚Üí Œµ) := Œµ, (Œµ ‚Üí œÉ) := œÉ, (Œµ ‚Üí Œµ) := Œµ, (œÅ √ó Œµ) := œÅ,
(Œµ√ó œÉ) := œÉ, (Œµ√ó Œµ) := Œµ:
œÑ(P tœÅ) := Œµ
