Theorem 3.6. Let T be the companion matrix of the n-degree primitive
polynomial f(x) = xn + cn‚àí1xn‚àí1 + cn‚àí2xn‚àí2 + ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑+ c1x+1. And let cn‚àí1 = 1
and T k + T k+1 = I for some k ‚àà N. Then ps(2) = k.
Proof. Since T k + T k+1 = I, T k+i + T k+(i+1) = T i(0 ‚â§ i ‚â§ n ‚àí 1). By Lemma
3.4, xk+i + xk+i+1 = xi(0 ‚â§ i ‚â§ n‚àí 1). That is,
sk+1,n + sk+2,n = 1,
sk+2,n‚àí1 + sk+3,n‚àí1 = 1,
...
sk+n,1 + sk+n+1,1 = 1.
Hence the 1st (resp. 2nd) elements of the (n ‚àí 1) vectors xkt, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ,xk+n‚àí2t
are the same. Suppose that the 1st and the 2nd elements of the (n ‚àí 1) vec-
tors xkt, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ,xk+n‚àí2t are of the form ‚Ä≤‚Ä≤0 ‚àó‚Ä≤‚Ä≤ . In the 1st column of S there
are two vectors (s11, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , sn‚àí1,1)t = (0, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , 0)t and (sk+1,1, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , sk+n‚àí1,1)t =
(0, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , 0)t. Since the 0-run of length n ‚àí 1 occurs exactly once in a PN se-
quence of period 2n ‚àí 1 by (P2), this is a contradiction. This means that the
1st and the 2nd elements of the (n ‚àí 1) vectors xkt, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ,xk+n‚àí2t must be of
the form ‚Ä≤‚Ä≤1 ‚àó‚Ä≤‚Ä≤ . Suppose that the 1st and the 2nd elements of the (n ‚àí 1) vec-
tors xkt, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ,xk+n‚àí2t are of the form ‚Ä≤‚Ä≤11‚Ä≤‚Ä≤. Since xk = (1, 1, ‚àó, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , ‚àó)t, xk+1 =
(1, ‚àó, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , ‚àó, 0)t + (cn‚àí1, cn‚àí2, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , c1, 1)t = (0, ‚àó, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , ‚àó, 1)t by Lemma 3.5. But
xk + xk+1 = (0, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , 0, 1)t. This is a contradiction. Thus the 1st and the 2nd
elements of the (n‚àí 1) vectors xkt, ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ,xk+n‚àí2t must be all ‚Ä≤‚Ä≤10‚Ä≤‚Ä≤. Since (n‚àí 1)
consecutive 0‚Ä≤s occur from the (k+1)th element to the (k+n‚àí 1)th element in
the 2nd column of S, ps(2) = k.
Example 3.7.We can find the phase shift ps(2) of the primitive polynomial
x7 + x6 + x5 + x4 + 1 by Theorem 3.6. Since T 86 + T 87 = I, ps(2) = 86.
