Corollary 3.10. Let T be the companion matrix of the n-degree primitive
polynomial f(x) = xn + cn‚àí1xn‚àí1 + cn‚àí2xn‚àí2 + ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑+ c1x+ 1. And let ci+1 = 1
and ci = ci‚àí1 = ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = c1 = 0. Then ps(k) = n‚àí k + 1(n‚àí i ‚â§ k ‚â§ n‚àí 1).
82 Sung-Jin Cho et al.
Theorem 3.11. Let T be the companion matrix of the n-degree primitive
polynomial f(x) = xn+ cn‚àí1xn‚àí1+ cn‚àí2xn‚àí2+ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑+ c1x+1. And let ci+1 = 0.
Then ps(n‚àí i‚àí 1) = ps(n‚àí i) + 1(0 ‚â§ i ‚â§ n‚àí 2).
Proof. Let ps(n ‚àí i) = p. Then sp+1,n‚àíi = sp+2,n‚àíi = ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = sp+(n‚àí1),n‚àíi = 0
and sp+n,n‚àíi = 1 by (P2). Since sk+1,n‚àíi‚àí1 = sk,n‚àíi + ci+1sk,1(1 ‚â§ k ‚â§ 2n ‚àí 2)
by Lemma 3.5 and ci+1 = 0,
sp+2,n‚àíi‚àí1 = sp+1,n‚àíi = 0,
sp+3,n‚àíi‚àí1 = sp+2,n‚àíi = 0,
...
sp+n,n‚àíi‚àí1 = sp+n‚àí1,n‚àíi = 0,
sp+n+1,n‚àíi‚àí1 = sp+n,n‚àíi = 1.
Thus ps(n‚àí i‚àí 1) = ps(n‚àí i) + 1.
Corollary 3.12. Let T be the companion matrix of the n-degree primitive
polynomial f(x) = xn + cn‚àí1xn‚àí1 + cn‚àí2xn‚àí2 + ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ + c1x + 1. And let ci+k =
ci+(k‚àí1) = ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = ci+1 = 0 and ps(n‚àí i) = p. Then ps(n‚àí i‚àí j) = ps(n‚àí i)+ j =
p+ j(1 ‚â§ j ‚â§ k).
Theorem 3.13. Let T be the companion matrix of the n-degree primitive
polynomial f(x) = xn + cn‚àí1xn‚àí1 + cn‚àí2xn‚àí2 + ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ + c1x + 1. And let cn‚àí1 =
¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = cn‚àím+1 = 0 and cn‚àím = 1. If T k + T k+m = I for some k ‚àà N, then
ps(m+ 1) = k.
Proof. Since T k + T k+m = I, T k+i + T k+m+i = T i(0 ‚â§ i ‚â§ n ‚àí 1). By Lemma
3.4, xk+i + xk+m+i = xi(0 ‚â§ i ‚â§ n ‚àí 1). Since xk + xk+m = x0, sk+1,m+1 =
¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = sk+m+2,m+1 = 0. From xk+i + xk+m+i = xi(1 ‚â§ i ‚â§ n ‚àí 1), we obtain
sk+m+3,m+1 = ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ = sk+(n‚àí1),m+1 = 0. Thus sk+1,m+1 = sk+2,m+1 = ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ =
sk+(n‚àí1),m+1 = 0 and sk+n,m+1 = 1. Hence by (P2) ps(m+ 1) = k.
Example 3.14. We can find the phase shift ps(3) = 14 of the primitive
polynomial x6 + x4 + x3 + x+ 1 by Theorem 3.13.
