Theorem 1. The notation ŒΩdmQ induces the same concept of computability as
the standard notation ŒΩQ (ŒΩdmQ ‚â° ŒΩQ)
Proof. (ŒΩQ ‚â§ ŒΩdmQ ). The translation from the notation ŒΩQ into ŒΩdmQ notation can
be done straight away by applying a modified version of the conventional school
division algorithm in which, when the fractional part is being obtained, we check
the repetition of partial remainders. Notice that this key issue is used for the
online-division algorithm proposed in Section 4. Therefore, we wrap the partial
remainders pr ‚àà dom (ŒΩZ) and then successively concatenate them with a given
word r ‚àà Œ£‚àó# ‚à™ {Œª} , which we initialize to Œª (r = rŒπw (pr)). On every iteration
related with the calculation of the fractional part, we check if the wrapped partial
remainder Œπw (pr) . In that case, we find the position of the subword by means
of a subword count function c : Œ£‚àó# ‚à™{Œª}√óŒ£‚àó# ‚Üí Z, which outputs the number
of words counted i ‚àà N when the partial remainder subword was found and then
the algorithm stops. Notice that, as usual, the algorithm can also stop when the
partial remainder is zero (pr = 0). If the partial remainder is not found (pr is
not a subword of r), then output ‚àí1.
Now, let q ‚àà dom (ŒΩQ) be the quotient obtained from the division, mf ‚àà
dom (ŒΩsd) the fixed mantissa and mp ‚àà dom
(
ŒΩsdZ
)
the periodic mantissa. Then
mf and mp are the following prefix and suffix from q, which are now translated
into signed digit based notations:
mf = ŒΩsd (q0 . . .  . . . qi) ,
mp = ŒΩsdZ (qi+1 . . .  . . . qj) ,
(12)
where j = |q| ‚àí 1.
Now, in order to normalize the rational number obtained:
Online-division with Periodic Rational Numbers 103
Define the count function c : dom (ŒΩsd)‚Üí dom (ŒΩN) , which outputs a natural
number corresponding to the position of the dot ‚Äù  ‚Äù in the input word. If the
dot ‚Äù  ‚Äù is not found, then the function outputs the length of the word.
Define the function a : Œ£‚àó √ó dom (ŒΩN) ‚Üí Œ£‚àó √ó dom (ŒΩZ) which removes the
