We define R(x, y) and its negation via two existential formulas:
„Äàx, y„Äâ ‚àà P ‚áî U(x)&U(y)&‚àÉz(W (z)&(f(z) = x)&(g(z) = y)),
„Äàx, y„Äâ /‚àà P ‚áî U(x)&U(y)&‚àÉz, t(W (z)&V (t)&(f(z) = x)&(g(z) = t)&(g(y) = t)).
It is easily seen from the definitions that D(x) and R(x, y) are invariant and
relatively intrinsically c.e. Now we check the properties (P0)‚Äì(P3).
(P0) Follows directly from the construction of the transformation.
(P1) Let G be a presentation of G. Existence of deg(G)‚Äìcomputable map follows
from the definition of f ,g and from defining formulas for BAG and RAG .
(P2) Let h be a 1‚Äìto-1 map ofD(A) ontoD(A) such that R(x, y)‚áî R(h(x), h(y)).
We extend h in the following way. For v ‚àà V we find the corresponding u ‚àà U
such that g(u) = v. After that we let h(v) = g(h(u)). For w ‚àà W we first
check if g(w) is in U or in V . If g(w) = u ‚àà U then we find the unique w‚Ä≤ ‚ààW
connected with h(u). Such w‚Ä≤ exists by properties of h. We let h(w) = w‚Ä≤.
The second case is similar.
(P3) Let G be a presentation of G. Every element v from V is the unique element
satisfying the formula (g(v) = v)&(g(u) = v)&(f(u) = u) for corresponding
u ‚àà D(AG)(= UAG). For w ‚àà W the formula depends on the value of g(w).
If g(w) ‚àà U then we write that there exists exactly one u ‚àà U which is the
value of g(w). Similar for g(w) ‚àà V .
Thus, we have proved the following theorems.
Theorem 5. Let G be a computably presentable graph. There exists a com-
putably presentable L0‚Äìstructure A such that for any degree d, A has the same
d‚Äìcomputable dimension as G.
