Similarly, we can construct a lifting in case D0 = [0, 1]√ó [0, 1]. The general case
can be proved easily by the previous two cases.
Next, we show ¬¨1‚Üí ¬¨2. We assume ¬¨WKL0. Let D0 = {(x, y) ‚äÜ R2 | ‚àí1 ‚â§
x ‚â§ 1,‚àí1 ‚â§ y ‚â§ 1}, D = ‚àÇD0, and X = R. Then we can take pi : X ‚Üí D
as a covering map by winding X on D. By ¬¨WKL0, there exists a continuous
function f : D0 ‚Üí D such that f |D = idD (by Shioji and Tanaka[2]). However,
there is no lifting of f .
The complete proof of the previous lemma is in [1].
Now we study Picard‚Äôs little theorem. For this, we consider a version of the
Riemann mapping theorem:
(‚àó) Let D be an interior of a simple closed curve on the Riemann sphere. Then,
D is conformally equivalent to the unit open ball B(0; 1) and a conformal map
h : D ‚Üí B(0; 1) can be expanded into a homeomorphism h¬Ø : D ‚Üí B(0, 1).
We prove Picard‚Äôs little theorem, which asserts that an entire function is a
constant if it omits two points, within WKL0 + (‚àó).
We reason within WKL0. Let f be an entire function which omits two points.
Without loss of generality, we assume that f : C ‚Üí C \ {0, 1}. By (‚àó) and
the Schwarz reflection principle, we can construct a holomorphic covering map
pi : B(0; 1) ‚Üí C \ {0, 1} in the usual way. Then, by Lemma 1, there exists a
holomorphic function fÀÜ : C ‚Üí B(0; 1) such that pi ‚ó¶ fÀÜ = f . By the Liouville
theorem, fÀÜ is constant. Thus, f is also constant and this completes the proof of
Picard‚Äôs little theorem.
Since a full version of Riemann mapping theorem is provable in ACA0, we
can prove Picard‚Äôs theorem within ACA0.
Theorem 13 (Picard‚Äôs theorem). The following is provable in ACA0. Let f
be a holomorphic function from C to C. If the range of f omits two points, then,
f is a constant function.
We conjecture that (‚àó) is provable withinWKL0, which implies thatWKL0 proves
Picard‚Äôs theorem. We have not managed the reversal of Picard‚Äôs little theorem.
