Proof. Functions (1) to (4) are easily seen to be multitape Œ±-computable with
majorizing functions the maximum input ordinal plus 1.
(5) We define a program to compute C. Move the heads of the tapes con-
taining Œ≥ and Œ¥ to the right to decide whether Œ≥ < Œ¥. According to the outcome
move the output tape's head together with the head of the tape containing Œæ
or Œ∂ to the right until a `1' is read. Copy the `1' to the output tape and stop.
This program runs at most MC(Œ≥, Œ¥, Œæ, Œ∂) = max{Œ≥, Œ¥} + max{Œæ, Œ∂} + 1-many
steps. Since Œ± is closed under PrimO functions and ordinal addition is PrimO
the program terminates and C is multitape Œ±-computable.
(a) Let g be k-Œ±-computable by a program Pg with parameters pig and ma-
