{(Ul, bl)}l‚â§n(u) ‚àà ConN.
We introduce a notion of ‚Äúrelative height‚Äù between partial numbers. Let
u, v ‚àà IdeN and n ‚àà GN. Say that u is above n, and write u  n, if it contains
information built from at least n constructors, that is, if either u N Sn‚àí10 or
u N Sn‚àó. Say further that u is above v, and write u  v, if it is above any
index below v, that is, if v  n ‚Üí u  n for all n ‚àà GN. Note that aboveness
is not antisymmetric, since Sn0  Sn+1‚ä• and Sn+1‚ä•  Sn0 for all n. It is also
obvious that aboveness between ideals is a total preorder with single maximum
element ‚àû and single minimum element ‚ä•, as well as that, for total ideals, it
reduces to the standard ‚â• relation.
This straightforward notion, which is merely based on the simple tree struc-
ture of the lazy natural numbers, is nevertheless the necessary and sufficient
step beyond the techniques used in the flat case. The calculus it provides is
summarized in the following.
Lemma 5. Concerning aboveness  ‚äÜ IdeN √ó IdeN the following hold.
1. If u N v then u  v.
2. If v  w and w  v then v = w for all v, w ‚äÜ u, u ‚àà IdeN.
3. If u 3N v and u  v then u N v.
4. If u  v and u 63N v then v ‚àà GN.
