2 Abstract Strategic Games
This section defines abstract strategic games and their Nash equilibria.
Abstract strategic games are strategic games whose real-valued payoff func-
tions are replaced with abstract outcomes. In addition for each agent, an arbi-
trary binary relation accounts explicitly for the agent‚Äôs preference over outcomes.
These relations replace the (implicit) usual total order over the real numbers.
Definition 1 (Abstract strategic games) Abstract strategic games are 4-
tuples „ÄàA, S, P, (‚ä≥a)a‚ààA„Äâ where:
‚Äì A is a non-empty set of agents,
‚Äì S =
‚äó
a‚ààA Sa is the Cartesian product of non-empty sets of strategies,
‚Äì P : S ‚Üí Oc is a function mapping strategy profiles to given outcomes,
‚Äì ‚ä≥a is a relation over outcomes, and o‚ä≥a o
‚Ä≤ says that agent a prefers o‚Ä≤ to o.
For s and s‚Ä≤ in S, s‚ä≥a s
‚Ä≤ stands for P (s)‚ä≥a P (s
‚Ä≤), by abuse of notation.
