The following definition makes use of the compactness in the topology we
just mentioned to define the meaning of ‚Äúbetter‚Äù œïÃÇ-programs in terms of query-
complexity.
Definition 4 (Query Speed-up). Let œïÃÇi = œïÃÇj.
1. We say that j is a weakly query sped-up version of i if and only if
Q[i<j] is compact and Q[i>j] is noncompact in Q(i, j).
If j is a weakly query sped-up version of i, we write œïÃÇi ‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇj.
2. We say that j is a strongly query sped-up version of i if and only if
Q[i<j] ‚à™Q[i=j] is compact in Q(i, j).
If j is a strongly query sped-up version of i, we write œïÃÇi ‚â∫‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇj. 
Suppose that we are to write a new œïÃÇ-program j for œïÃÇi. Intuitively, if the new
œïÃÇ-program j can improve the query-complexity on a ‚Äúlarge‚Äù (noncompact) set
of inputs and leaves a ‚Äúsmall‚Äù (compact) set of inputs on which j queries more
than i does, we say that j is a weakly query sped-up version of i. Note that, we do
not care how many inputs on which the query-complexity remains unchanged.
Since T(œïÃÇj) ‚äÜ Q(i, j), it follows that, if Q[i<j] is compact in Q(i, j), so is it in
T(œïÃÇj), and hence we can patch œïÃÇ-program j on Q[i<j] so that the patched œïÃÇ-
program will never query more than i does. Whereas, if œïÃÇ-program j is a strongly
query sped-up version of i, then the set on which j does not improve its query-
complexity must be ‚Äúsmall‚Äù (compact). Note that, if Q[i<j] ‚à™Q[i=j] is compact
in Q(i, j), then Q[i>j] must be noncompact in Q(i, j). Clearly, for œïÃÇi = œïÃÇj , we
have the following implication:
œïÃÇi ‚â∫‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇj =‚áí œïÃÇi ‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇj .
Query-Optimal Oracle Turing Machines for Type-2 Computations 299
Definition 5 (Query-optimal œïÃÇ-programs). Let F : T √óN‚Üí N be a com-
putable functional. Let e be a œïÃÇ-program for F .
1. We say that e is an absolute query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F if and only if,
on every (f, x) ‚àà T √óN, the OTM MÃÇe does not make unnecessary queries
during the course of computing œïÃÇe(f, x).
2. We say that e is a strong query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F if and only if
there is no œïÃÇ-program i for F such that, œïÃÇe ‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇi.
3. We say that e is a weak query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F if and only if there
is no œïÃÇ-program i for F such that, œïÃÇe ‚â∫‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇi. 
Definition 5 gives us three versions of query-optimal œïÃÇ-programs, where ver-
sion 1 is the strongest notion and version 3 is the weakest one. Suppose that e is
a œïÃÇ-program for F : T √óN‚Üí N. The following implications are straightforward:
1. If e is an absolute query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F , then it is also a strong
query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F .
2. If e is an strong query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F , then it is also a weak
query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for F .
Moreover, if T(œïÃÇe) = Q(e), then e is an absolute query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for
œïÃÇe. We shall argue that the stronger the notion of query-optimum, the easier
we can obtain a speed-up theorem. In other words, it is more difficult to obtain
a query-optimal OTM when the notion of query-optimum becomes stronger.
However, we do not know if the speed-up phenomenon still exists under our
weakest notion of query-optimum; neither do we know how far can one weaken
the notion of query-optimal programs to do away the speed-up phenomenon
while keeping the notion nontrivial. We give partial results in the next section.
4 Query-optimal Programs
With a fixed complexity measure that satisfies Blum‚Äôs axioms, the original speed-
up theorem states that there is a total computable function without optimal
program for it. Although query-complexity does not satisfy the Blum‚Äôs axioms,
each of the three versions of query-optimal programs gives rise to the following
questions:
1. Does every computable functional F : T √ó N ‚Üí N always have a query-
optimal œïÃÇ-program for it?
2. If the answer to the first question is negative, then can we construct the
query-speed-able functional?
3. If a given F : T √ó N ‚Üí N does have a query-optimal œïÃÇ-programs for it,
then can we uniformly construct a query-optimal program for F from an
arbitrary œïÃÇ-program for F?
4. Suppose there is no query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for œïÃÇe0 : T √óN ‚Üí N. Can
we effectively construct an infinite sequence of query-sped-up version of œïÃÇ-
programs from e0? That is, can we have e0, e1, e2, . . . such that, for each
i ‚àà N, ei+1 is a query-sped-up version of ei?
300 Chung-Chih Li
We have a positive answer to the second question with respect to the abso-
lute and strong versions of query-optimal programs. Thus, a negative answer to
the first question follows immediately. Compared to the original nonconstruc-
tive speed-up theorem, the speedable functional for the second question is very
simple. However, we do not know if there is a computable F : T √ó N ‚Üí N
that can forever strongly speed-up, i.e., we do not know if there is a computable
F : T √óN ‚Üí N without a weak query-optimal œïÃÇ-program. The answer to the
third question is negative given by Theorem 4. The fourth question is still open.
That is, given œïÃÇe0 : T √óN‚Üí N that is known to be speedable, we do not know
if there is an effective way to construct a sequence of œïÃÇ-programs such that,
œïÃÇe0 ‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇe1 ‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇe2 ‚â∫‚àóQ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑
or similarly,
œïÃÇe0 ‚â∫‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇe1 ‚â∫‚â∫‚àóQ œïÃÇe2 ‚â∫‚â∫‚àóQ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ .
Let œïe(x) ‚Üìs denote the case that the Turing Machine Me, on x, halts in s
steps. We now define a useful functional K : T √óN‚Üí N in the following.
Definition 6. Define K : T √óN‚Üí N by
K(f, x) =
{
œïx(x) + 1 if œïx(x) ‚Üìs, where s =
‚àëf(0)
i=0 f(i);
0 otherwise.

Let H denote the set {x|œïx(x) ‚Üì}. For any (f, x) ‚àà T √óN, if x 6‚àà H, then
any œïÃÇ-program that computes K, on input (f, x), may ask arbitrarily many
unnecessary queries, where the number of queries depends on the value of f(0).
It is easy to prove that there is no œïÃÇ-program for K with all unnecessary queries
removed (Theorem 1). Even if we lower the standard to strong query-optimal
programs, we still cannot have a query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for K (Theorem 2).
Theorem 3 states that K does have a weak query-optimal program for it.
Theorem 1. K has no absolute query-optimal œïÃÇ-program.
Proof: We show that from an absolute query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for K, if any,
one can construct a solution to the halting problem.
Suppose, by contradiction, œïÃÇe is an absolute query-optimal œïÃÇ-program for
K. Clearly, if x 6‚àà H, then for any f ‚àà T , K(f, x) = 0. On the other hand, if
x ‚àà H, there must be two distinct f, g ‚àà T such that œïÃÇe(f, x) 6= œïÃÇe(g, x). Thus,
some queries to the oracles f and g must be made. Therefore, given any x ‚àà N,
we can run œïÃÇe(‚àÖ‚àº0, x) first, where ‚àÖ‚àº0 is the zero everywhere function. Then, if
no queries were made during the course of computation, we know that x 6‚àà H.
Hence, N‚àíH is recursively enumerable, a contradiction. 
Theorem 2. K has no strong query-optimal œïÃÇ-program.
