that there is z coprime with both x and y such that there is w divisible by z
and each power pi of prime p 6= z (i ‚â§ n) divides w exactly when pi divides x,
but no such w exists for y and z. The main difference is that now the ordering
is defined up to ‚âàn instead of ‚âà.
The only relation which should be defined essentially in a different way is
W . This is so because now ind(x) is the index of x in a more subtle ordering.
However also in this case the argument from [18] can be repeated in extenso.
5 Summarizing FM representability theorem
In this final section we collect together all the results about the notions equivalent
to FM‚Äìrepresentability in one theorem.
Theorem 11 (The FM‚Äìrepresentability theorem and equivalent no-
tions). Let R be a relation on natural numbers. Then the following are equiva-
lent:
1. R is recursive with recursively enumerable oracle; ( ‚Äì in terms of oracle
machines)
342 Marcin Mostowski
2. R is of degree ‚â§ 0‚Ä≤; ( ‚Äì in terms of Turing degrees)
3. R is ‚àÜ02 in arithmetical hierarchy; ( ‚Äì in terms of arithmetical definability)
4. R is recursive in the limit; ( ‚Äì in terms of limits)
5. R is FM-representable (in FM(N,√ó,+)); ( ‚Äì just FM‚Äìrepresentablity)
6. R is statistically representable; ( ‚Äì in terms of density)
7. R is mathematically learnable; ( ‚Äì in terms of algorithmic learning)
8. R is Zeno decidable; ( ‚Äì in terms of hypercomputations)
9. R is FM‚Äìrepresentable in the divisibility FM‚Äìdomain.
