The last condition occurring here is quite strong and implies that there cannot
be too much elementsm generating non-trivial self-similar sets in arbitrary finite
fields. Look at the case F192 = F361 seen as F19[x] where x2+1 = 0. Encode the
element ax+b in the natural number 19a+b. I do not mention both m and m‚àí1
because they produce mirrored carpets. Also, if m has been already mentioned,
I don‚Äôt mention its Frobenius m19, because it produces the same carpet. So, up
to Frobenius and multiplicative inverse, one has non-trivial self-similar carpets
over F361 if and only if m is equal with one of the following 29 elements: 0, 1, 2,
3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 9, 14, 19, 21, 35, 47, 52, 53, 56, 63, 69, 76, 78, 88, 92, 102, 130, 136,
137, 148, 168. Values of m ‚àà F361 which are not itself, inverses of, or Frobenius
of elements in this list generate however interesting coloured images. Over the
prime fields Fp the situation looks better:
2.4 Fp as a field of self-similar carpets
Theorem 3. Let p be a prime and m ‚àà Fp. Exactly one of the following situa-
tions arrises:
1. m = 0. In this case I is a self-similar Pascal Triangle, I is only symmetric
through the first diagonal, and the group of symmetries of I is isomorphic
with S2.
Polynomial Iterations over Finite Fields 393
2. m = ¬±1. In this case I is a full square (for m = ‚àí1) or a nontrivial self-
similar set (for m = 1) and the group of symmetries of I is the full dyhedral
group D8 of the square.
3. p ‚â• 5, m ‚àà Fp \ {‚àí1, 0, 1}. In this case I is a non-trivial self-similar set
and the group of symmetries of I is generated by the reflexions through the
diagonals of the square. This group is isomorphic with Klein‚Äôs group K4.
Proof. Let now m ‚àà Fp \ {0}, let K be the group generated by the symmetries
through the both diagonals (isomorphic with Klein‚Äôs group K4) and let G be
the group of symmetries of I. From Lemma 7 it follows that K ‚â§ G ‚â§ D8. If
m = ‚àí1 then I is the full square and trivially G = D8. If m = 1 than it follows
from Lemma 7 that:
Œ¥F (p, 1) = Œ£Œ¥F (p, 1),
because 1‚àí1 = 1 so G is strictly bigger than K which already has 4 elements,
hence G = D8.
The converse is easy to prove using Lemma 4.
2.5 The special case m ‚àà {‚àí2,‚àí2‚àí1}: Diagonal Carpets
For m = ‚àí2 one has a1,1 = 0. Mirror-symmetric: for m = ‚àí2‚àí1 one has a1,p‚àí2 =
0. In fact, in these cases, all the elements of odd index on the corresponding
diagonal are zero!
Definition 10. Call first odd diagonal (respectively second odd diagonal)
the following set of indexes:
D+ = {(i, i) | 0 < i < p‚àí 1 ‚àß 2 6 | i}.
D‚àí = {(i, j) | i+ j = p‚àí 1 ‚àß 2 6 | i}.
Theorem 4. Let p ‚â• 5 be a prime. Following statements hold: D+ consists of
zeros of F (p,‚àí2) and D‚àí consists of zeros of F (p,‚àí2‚àí1). Moreover, the elements
of even index on the respective diagonals are 6= 0.
Proof. We prove that for m = ‚àí2 ‚àà Z the recurrent function f : N √ó N ‚Üí Z
defined in the second section has the property f(2s+1, 2s+1) = 0 for all k ‚àà N.
