Having completed the formula Œ¶(X,n,m) we can now restate the existence of a
winning strategy for the first player in W11.
A winning strategy in chomp is just a function S : X ‚Üí Y , which maps
configurations to configurations, so that whoever plays by S, wins. It is well
known that the first player has a winning strategy. How can this be stated?
As follows: ‚àÄY , such that Y has nm/2 many segments of length (n +m) each,
there exists an X as above, such that every other segment of X is Y , and
X [i+1] = S(Y [i]), and Œ¶(X,n,m), and also the first time the final configuration
occurs, it is in an even segment (so second player loses).
We want to say that given any configuration C as an initial configuration,
either player 1 or player 2 has a winning strategy. This can be stated as follows:
‚àÄC‚àÉS[WinP1(S, C) ‚à®WinP2(S, C)], (1)
where WinPi(S, C) (i ‚àà {0, 1}, and i¬Ø will denote the value in the set {0, 1}‚àí{i})
asserts that if player i plays by strategy S, then player i wins. This can be easily
state as follows: ‚àÄY (where Y is a sequence of moves of player i¬Ø), if it is player
i‚Äôs move on configuration C, and player i plays C ‚Ä≤ = S(C), then player i¬Ø will
end up with the poisoned square. Note that (1) is a Œ£B1 formula since the ‚Äú‚àÄC‚Äù
is bounded by the size of the chomp grid‚Äîwe omit the bound for clarity, and
WinPi is a Œ£
