0 formula.
Theorem 1. W11 ‚ä¢ ‚àÄC‚àÉS[WinP1(S, C) ‚à®WinP2(S, C)].
Proof. We prove it by induction on |C|, where we let |C| is the number of squares
in configuration C (in particular, if C consists of the poisoned square only, then
|C| = 1). The basis case is simple: if |C| = 1, then P1 loses, so in particular
‚àÉSWinP2(S, C) holds (and it does not matter what S is, since P2 will not use it
anyways).
For the induction step, suppose that the claim holds for all C such that
|C| ‚â§ n. Consider some C ‚Ä≤ such that |C ‚Ä≤| = n+ 1. We want to show that
‚àÉS[WinP1(S, C
‚Ä≤) ‚à®WinP2(S, C
‚Ä≤)]. (2)
Let C ‚Ä≤‚Ä≤ be the result of P1 making a move; since P1 must select some square,
it follows that |C ‚Ä≤‚Ä≤| < |C ‚Ä≤|, and so we can apply the induction hypothesis to
