= T,
where Tn is the first n bits of the base-two expansion of T . This is just a fixed
point theorem on compression rate, which reflects the self-referential nature of
the question.
The works [7, 8] on ‚Ñ¶D might be regarded as an elaboration of the technique
used by Chaitin [3] to prove that ‚Ñ¶ is random. The results of this paper may
be regarded as further elaborations of the technique. Due to the 10-page limit,
we omit most proofs. A full paper describing the details of the proofs is in
preparation.3
2 Preliminaries
We start with some notation about numbers and strings which will be used in
this paper. N = {0, 1, 2, 3, . . . } is the set of natural numbers, and N+ is the set
of positive integers. Q is the set of rational numbers, and R is the set of real
numbers. {0, 1}‚àó = {Œª, 0, 1, 00, 01, 10, 11, 000, 001, 010, . . . } is the set of finite
binary strings, where Œª denotes the empty string. For any s ‚àà {0, 1}‚àó, |s| is the
length of s. A subset S of {0, 1}‚àó is called a prefix-free set if no string in S is a
prefix of another string in S. {0, 1}‚àû is the set of infinite binary strings, where
an infinite binary string is infinite to the right but finite to the left. For any
Œ± ‚àà {0, 1}‚àû and any n ‚àà N+, Œ±n is the prefix of Œ± of length n. For any partial
function f , the domain of definition of f is denoted by dom f . We write ‚Äúr.e.‚Äù
instead of ‚Äúrecursively enumerable.‚Äù
Normally, o(n) denotes any function f : N+ ‚Üí R such that limn‚Üí‚àû f(n)/n =
0. On the other hand, O(1) denotes any function g : N+ ‚Üí R such that there is
C ‚àà R with the property that |g(n)| ‚â§ C for all n ‚àà N+.
Let T be an arbitrary real number. T mod 1 denotes T ‚àí bT c, where bT c is
the greatest integer less than or equal to T . Hence, T mod 1 ‚àà [0, 1). We identify
a real number T with the infinite binary string Œ± such that 0.Œ± is the base-two
expansion of T mod 1 with infinitely many zeros. Thus, Tn denotes the first n
bits of the base-two expansion of T mod 1 with infinitely many zeros.
We say that a real number T is computable if there exists a total recursive
function f : N+ ‚Üí Q such that |T ‚àí f(n)| < 1/n for all n ‚àà N+. We say that
T is right-computable if there exists a total recursive function g : N+ ‚Üí Q such
that T ‚â§ g(n) for all n ‚àà N+ and limn‚Üí‚àû g(n) = T . We say that T is left-
computable if ‚àíT is right-computable. It is then easy to see that, for any T ‚àà R,
T is computable if and only if T is both right-computable and left-computable.
See e.g. Weihrauch [12] for the detail of the treatment of the computability of
real numbers and real functions on a discrete set.
3 The details of the proofs are also available in an extended and electronic version of
this paper at URL: http://arxiv.org/abs/0801.4194v1
