2.1 Algorithmic information theory
In the following we concisely review some definitions and results of algorithmic
information theory [3, 4]. A computer is a partial recursive function C : {0, 1}‚àó ‚Üí
{0, 1}‚àó such that domC is a prefix-free set. For each computer C and each
s ‚àà {0, 1}‚àó, HC(s) is defined by HC(s) = min
{ |p| ‚à£‚à£ p ‚àà {0, 1}‚àó & C(p) = s}. A
computer U is said to be optimal if for each computer C there exists a constant
sim(C) with the following property; if C(p) is defined, then there is a p‚Ä≤ for
which U(p‚Ä≤) = C(p) and |p‚Ä≤| ‚â§ |p|+sim(C). It is easy to see that there exists an
optimal computer. Note that the class of optimal computers equals to the class
of functions which are computed by universal self-delimiting Turing machines
(see Chaitin [3] for the detail). We choose a particular optimal computer U as
the standard one for use, and define H(s) as HU (s), which is referred to as the
program-size complexity of s or the Kolmogorov complexity of s.
Chaitin‚Äôs halting probability ‚Ñ¶ is defined by
‚Ñ¶ =
‚àë
p‚ààdomU
2‚àí|p|.
For any Œ± ‚àà {0, 1}‚àû, we say that Œ± is weakly Chaitin random if there exists c ‚àà N
such that n‚àí c ‚â§ H(Œ±n) for all n ‚àà N+ [3, 4]. Then Chaitin [3] showed that ‚Ñ¶ is
weakly Chaitin random. For any Œ± ‚àà {0, 1}‚àû, we say that Œ± is Chaitin random
if limn‚Üí‚àûH(Œ±n) ‚àí n = ‚àû [3, 4]. It is then shown that, for any Œ± ‚àà {0, 1}‚àû, Œ±
is weakly Chaitin random if and only if Œ± is Chaitin random (see Chaitin [4] for
the proof and historical detail). Thus ‚Ñ¶ is Chaitin random.
In the works [7, 8], we generalized the notion of the randomness of an infinite
binary string so that the degree of the randomness can be characterized by a
real number D with 0 < D ‚â§ 1 as follows.
Definition 1 (weak Chaitin D-randomness and D-compressibility). Let
D ‚àà R with D ‚â• 0, and let Œ± ‚àà {0, 1}‚àû. We say that Œ± is weakly Chaitin
D-random if there exists c ‚àà N such that Dn ‚àí c ‚â§ H(Œ±n) for all n ‚àà N+.
We say that Œ± is D-compressible if H(Œ±n) ‚â§ Dn + o(n), which is equivalent to
limn‚Üí‚àûH(Œ±n)/n ‚â§ D. uunionsq
In the case of D = 1, the weak Chaitin D-randomness results in the weak
Chaitin randomness. For any D ‚àà [0, 1] and any Œ± ‚àà {0, 1}‚àû, if Œ± is weakly
Chaitin D-random and D-compressible, then
