For the space complexity classes, we can likewise proceed by simply defining
space(x, T ) as the largest Œ± that occurs as the position of the head at some
stage of the computation:
Definition 2.6. If T is a machine that, at one point reaches the halting state
qf , and time(x, T ) = Œ±, we define space(x, T ) = sup{hTŒ≤ (x) : Œ≤ ‚â§ Œ±}.
Definition 2.7. For any OTM T , we say that T is a space f machine if, for
all x ‚àà R, we have space(x, T ) ‚â§ f(x). For any ordinal Œæ, we say that T is a
space Œæ machine if T is a space f machine for the constant function f such
that f(x) = Œæ for all x ‚àà R.
Definition 2.8. For any function f , we let PSPACEKf denote the class of all
sets of reals that are decidable by a space f machine. For any ordinal Œæ, we let
PSPACEKŒæ denote the class of all sets of reals that are decidable by a space Œ∑
machine for some Œ∑ < Œæ.
An immediate result of these definitions (see [Lo¬®]), is that a computation of
a ordinal Turing machine can never take more space than it can take time:
Proposition 2.9. For all f and all Œ±, we have PKf ‚äÜ PSPACEKf and PKŒ± ‚äÜ
PSPACEKŒ± respectively.
We will now introduce the notions of clockable, writable, eventually writable,
and accidentally writable ordinals. All these notions were originally defined in
[HaLe], from page 581 onward. Note that the these notions refer to writability
by ITTMs, rather than by OTMs!
Definition 2.10. We call an ordinal Œ± x-clockable if there is an ITTM that
terminates at time Œ± starting from input x. An ordinal Œ± is x-writable if there
is an ITTM that terminates with a code for Œ± on the output tape, starting from
input x. An ordinal Œ± is eventually x-writable if there is an ITTM that, on
2 The < here and in Definition 2.8 is correct, and should not be a ‚â§. A justification
for this is found in the fact that using < instead of ‚â§ here allows for a larger variety
of classes‚Äìa broader discussion on the exact nature of these definitions can be found
in Appendix A of [Wi].
466 Joost Winter
input x, at one point writes a code for Œ± on the out tape, never to change it
afterwards, without necessarily terminating. An ordinal Œ± is accidentally x-
writable if there is an ITTM that, on input x, writes Œ± on any of the tapes at
some stage of the computation.
With clockable, writable, etc., we mean ‚àÖ-clockable, -writable, etc.
We call the supremum of x-writable ordinals Œªx, the supremum of x-clockable
ordinals Œ≥x, the supremum of eventually x-writable ordinals Œ∂x, and the supre-
mum of accidentally x-writable ordinals Œ£x.
It turns out that the notions of clockability, writability, eventually and acci-
dentally writability are related in the following way:
Proposition 2.11. For all reals x, Œ≥x = Œªx, and Œªx < Œ∂x < Œ£x.
Proof. See [We, Corollary 2.1], and for a corrected and more detailed version,
[Wi, Proposition 3.16].
3 Variants on the ordinal Turing machine architecture
It turns out that the exact number of tapes used by an OTM is generally irrel-
evant, and that, as long as there is just one head used for these tapes, OTMs
with more tapes can be simulated by OTMs with less tapes, and vice versa.
Proposition 3.1. For any n ‚àà N, with n > 2, a set A ‚äÜ R is decidable by an
OTM with n tapes if and only it is decidable by a ordinal Turing machine with
2 tapes.
Proof. Because we only are considering sets of reals here, we only have to deal
with inputs that are real numbers. Assume that A is decidable by a ordinal
Turing machine T with n tapes. We can now construct a ordinal Turing machine
T ‚Ä≤ with 2 tapes as follows:
‚Äì T ‚Ä≤ starts out by stretching the input such that, if x is the input, after the
stretching operation we find {(n ‚àí 1) ¬∑ k : k ‚àà x} on the first tape. We can
use a signal state to recognize when we are done with this operation, and
ensure this signal state only reads 1s at successor ordinals; at stage œâ we will
find ourselves with the head at position œâ, in this signal state, and read a 0,
and move left so that the head position will again be 0.
‚Äì After this, we simulate the original n tape machine on our 2 tape machine,
using the second tape to simulate the output tape, and the first tape to
simulate the n‚àí1 other tapes. We make sure that we have a fixed number k
such that each step by T is simulated by k steps of T ‚Ä≤, and moreover ensure
that, for any ordinal Œ± such that Œ± = k ¬∑ Œ≤ for some k, hTŒ±(x) = (n ‚àí 1) ¬∑ Œ∑
for some Œ∑.
Because the only tape being simulated on the second tape is the original
second tape, and because first cell of the second tape of T corresponds to the
first cell of the second tape of T ‚Ä≤, it follows that T and T ‚Ä≤ will, on the same
input values, always give the same output values.
Space Complexity in Ordinal Turing Machines 467
This gives us the following corollary:
Corollary 3.2. For any m,n ‚â• 2, a set A is decidable by a ordinal Turing
machine with m tapes if and only if it is decidable by a ordinal Turing machine
with n tapes.
Furthermore, it has been conjectured that this is also true in the case where
n = 1.
4 Time complexity for ordinal Turing machines
We can prove a number of theorems about time complexity for ordinal Turing
machines: to start with, it turns out that for many recursive ordinals Œ±, a ordinal
Turing machine can compute exactly the same sets in time Œ± that an ITTM
machine can. The first theorem is a modification of [Lo¬®, Proposition 4].
It should be noted that, with sufficiently closed Œ± and/or f , PHKŒ± ‚äÜ PKŒ± and
PHKf ‚äÜ PKf always follow. To simulate a Hamkins-Kidder machine by a Koepke
machine, we only need to take care of finding a way to recognize when we are
at a limit stage of the computation (which can be achieved through the use of
flags on an auxiliary tape), then move left, and move to a special limit state.
This ‚Äòmoving left‚Äô might take at most œâ steps, and hence, the inequality holds
for any ordinal Œ± such that œâ √ó Œ± = œâ.
Proposition 4.1. For any recursive ordinal Œ± larger than œâ2, where Œ± is the
successor of a limit ordinal Œ≤, and œâ √ó Œ≤ = Œ≤, we have PHKŒ± = PKŒ± .
Proof. Assume that A ‚àà PKŒ± . This means that A is decidable by a time Œ∑ machine
for some Œ∑ < Œ±, which, because Œ± = Œ≤+1, here can be restated as: A is decidable
by a time Œ≤ OTM. Then A is, by Proposition 2.9, decidable by a time Œ≤ OTM
that uses Œ≤ or less cells. Because Œ≤ is a recursive ordinal, we can let an infinite
time Turing machine write a code for Œ≤ on the tape in œâ steps. After that, we
can simulate the algorithm of the ordinal Turing machine, which needs Œ≤ cells,
on our œâ-sized tape. Because every step of the simulated computation will be
simulated by a finite number of steps of the simulating computation, and because
the simulated computation takes less than Œ≤ steps (the halting state cannot be
reached at Œ≤ itself, because Œ≤ is a limit ordinal), the simulating computation
will also take less than Œ≤ steps. At limit stages, we still need to find which the
lim inf of the visited tape positions, which might take œâ steps: hence, a single
step might be simulated by œâ steps in the simulation.
Because Œ≤ ‚â• œâ2, the complete algorithm will take less than œâ + (œâ √ó Œ≤) = Œ≤
steps in total.
This equivalence between the time complexity classes of OTMs and ITTMs
also holds at the level Œª, the supremum of all writable ordinals:
Proposition 4.2. PHKŒª = P
K
Œª .
468 Joost Winter
Proof. Assume that A is decidable by a time Œ± OTM T , where Œ± < Œª (or, in
other words, where Œ± is a writable ordinal). This machine T is also a space Œ±
machine, so the computation uses at most Œ± cells. Say, Œ± is writable by an ITTM
in time Œ≤: this implies that Œ≤ is clockable and hence also writable. After writing
a code for Œ± on the tape in Œ≤ steps, we can continue by simulating the OTM
algorithm by simulating a tape of size Œ±, in time less than Œ±. Thus, we can
decide A with an ITTM in time Œ≤+Œ±, which is again a writable ordinal. Hence,
A ‚àà PHKŒª .
It turns out, that in fact, an equality of the above type still holds up to the
level Œ£x, the supremum of all ordinals accidentally writable on input x. Note
here that PKŒ£x is taken to mean P
K
f for the function f such that f(x) = Œ£
x for
all x.
Proposition 4.3. PKŒ£x = P
HK
Œªx .
Proof. Assume that a set A is in PKŒ£x . Then it follows from Proposition 2.9
that A is in PSPACEKŒ£x , and we know that there is an accidentally x-writable
ordinal Œ± such that, if we can write Œ± on the tape, we can compute A on an
ITTM, simulating an Œ±-sized fragment of the tape of the OTM within space œâ,
based upon the just-found coding of Œ±.
The tactic now is to construct an ITTM, that simulates all other ITTMs on
input x, and in doing so, performs an algorithm that, one by one, writes all reals
that are accidentally writable from x on one of the scratch tapes. We can be sure
that every real that is accidentally writable from x will be written on one of the
scratch tapes at some point; and, each time a real is written on the scratch tape
this way, we check if it codes an ordinal. If it does, we continue simulating the
computation using this ordinal as tape length: eventually we will either run out
of space, in which case we continue the algorithm writing accidentally writable
reals on the tape, or it will turn out that we have sufficient space, in which case
the computation will finish.
This computation will eventually halt, because a real coding an ordinal equal
to or larger than Œ± will be written on the tape at some point and, as all halting
computations will halt before Œªx, we know that the computation will halt before
Œªx. So, it follows that the set A is in PHKŒªx .
This gives us the following corollary:
Corollary 4.4. PKŒ£x = Dec
HK
Proof. This follows directly from DecHK = PHKŒªx and P
K
Œ£x = P
HK
Œªx .
5 Space complexity for OTMs
Now we will take a quick look look at space complexity issues for Koepke-type
Ordinal machines.
Proposition 5.1. DecHK ‚äÜ PSPACEKœâ+2
Space Complexity in Ordinal Turing Machines 469
Proof. Assume that A ‚àà DecHK. We now can simulate an algorithm deciding A
on an OTM with tape length œâ + 1 by moving left towards position 0 at limit
states, and besides this, simply performing the algorithm used by the ITTM.
Proposition 5.2. PSPACEKŒ£x ‚äÜ DecHK
Proof. In the proof Proposition 4.3, it was shown that PSPACEKŒ£x ‚äÜ PHKŒªx . In
combination with the fact that PHKŒªx = Dec
HK, this gives the desired result.
These two results combined give an interesting result: together they imply
that it does not really matter how much extra space you use on an OTM, as
long as it does not go beyond Œ£x. In particular, we have:
Corollary 5.3. For any ordinal Œ±, such that Œ± ‚â• œâ+1 and Œ± ‚â§ Œ£+1, and for
any function f such that we have f(x) ‚â• œâ and f(x) ‚â§ Œ£x for all x, we have
respectively that PSPACEKŒ± = Dec
HK or PSPACEKf = Dec
HK.
So, it turns out that, even with space Œ£x at our disposal, we are unable to
compute any functions that an ITTM cannot compute. Moreover, we can now
establish a relationship between the PSPACEK-classes and the PK-classes in a
few cases.
Proposition 5.4. For any ordinal Œ±, such that Œ± ‚â• œâ + 1 and Œ± ‚â§ Œª, we have
that PKŒ± ( PSPACE
K
Œ± .
Proof. On one side, we know from Corollary 5.3 that PSPACEKŒ± = Dec
HK,
and on the other side, we know that PKŒ± ( Dec
HK.
Proposition 5.5. For functions f such that, for all x, Œ£x > f(x) > Œªx, we
have PSPACEKf = P
K
f = Dec
HK.
Proof. On one side, from Corollary 5.3 it follows that PSPACEKf = Dec
HK.
On the other side, we know that PKf ‚äá PKŒªx , and from Proposition 4.3 we know
that PKŒªx = P
